Blue

Target IP: 10.10.63.218

Deploy & hack into a Windows machine, leveraging common misconfigurations issues.

Reconnaissance


There are seven TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.



Performing an aggressive nmap scan returns the interesting result above. It looks like the target machine is running Windows 7 Professional 7601 Service Pack 1.


Using the nmap flag --script=vuln, I obtained the crucial information above. It looks like the SMB that is running on the target machine is vulnerable to remote code execution. This msf17-010 vulnerability has the CVE ID of CVE-2017-0143; therefore, it is like infamous EternalBlue.

Enumeration


Using crackmapexec, I obtained more information about the target machine especially the platform. It seems like the target is running Windows 7 Professional x64.


I found the working exploit above on Github. I downloaded this on my machine. Time to exploit the target machine.

Exploitation


I started a listener on port 8443 on my machine. And using the exploit, I initialised the RHOST, LHOST, and LPORT.


Then I obtained the reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 with the session as NT authority\system. Now I have a foothold on the target machine. No need to escalate my privileges as the session belongs to the user system.
